world.

00:05:34.490 --> 00:05:36.550
I'm also going to throw in some technical
tips

00:05:36.550 --> 00:05:37.550
here.

00:05:37.550 --> 00:05:39.259
You see that everything in this scene here
is in focus from the

00:05:39.259 --> 00:05:42.460
ship in the back to the foreground here.

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:44.650
To get
everything into scene and focus, what you

00:05:44.650 --> 00:05:49.259
want to do is
use a wide angle lens, set a small aperture,

00:05:49.259 --> 00:05:51.940
and focus
1/3 into the scene.

00:05:51.940 --> 00:05:53.059
Now that may sound backwards.

00:05:53.059 --> 00:05:54.830
You
might think oh, that's so far away.

00:05:54.830 --> 00:05:57.360
I want to focus 2/3
into the scene.

00:05:57.360 --> 00:05:59.879
You focus 1/3 into the scene.

00:05:59.879 --> 00:06:03.169
That'll
give you the -- a maximum amount of the scene

00:06:03.169 --> 00:06:04.169
in focus.

00:06:04.169 --> 00:06:06.509
You're really setting the lens up for what's
called the

00:06:06.509 --> 00:06:07.509
hyperfocal point.

00:06:07.509 --> 00:06:10.380
But I fell in love with this
beautiful blue ice.

00:06:10.380 --> 00:06:12.129
Just look at these formations.

00:06:12.129 --> 00:06:15.710
