00:11:04.910 --> 00:11:08.410
So I have
the telephoto lens on the crop sensor camera

00:11:08.410 --> 00:11:11.800
because
animals are far away that crop sensor doesn't

00:11:11.800 --> 00:11:13.850
really
bring you closer, but it's like you're getting

00:11:13.850 --> 00:11:14.850
closer.

00:11:14.850 --> 00:11:18.180
And on the full frame image sensor camera
what I have is

00:11:18.180 --> 00:11:22.800
a wide angle zoom, usually a 17 to 40-millimeter
zoom,

00:11:22.800 --> 00:11:27.000
maybe a 24 to 105-millimeter zoom, and I always
have a

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:28.990
fish eye with me, too.

00:11:28.990 --> 00:11:32.060
I don't carry a lot of lenses,
as Susan will tell you.

00:11:32.060 --> 00:11:35.021
I don't have a lot of lenses --
actually, I don't have a lot of lenses so

00:11:35.021 --> 00:11:36.310
I don't carry
a lot of lenses.

00:11:36.310 --> 00:11:38.340
You don't need, you know, a ton of
lenses.

00:11:38.340 --> 00:11:41.610
I lead workshops where people show up and
they

00:11:41.610 --> 00:11:43.650
have those belts, you know, and they have
like eight

00:11:43.650 --> 00:11:46.590
lenses here, they have their backpacks with
nine more

00:11:46.590 --> 00:11:49.480
lenses here, and they miss all the shots.

00:11:49.480 --> 00:11:52.850
I like to
have my cameras handy over one shoulder, if

00:11:52.850 --> 00:11:55.800
I have the
wide angle lens -- wide angle lens -- wide

00:11:55.800 --> 00:11:58.540
angle zoom on
my camera body and on the other -- the telephoto.

00:11:58.540 --> 00:12:04.720
Anyway, this was taken with the 100 to 400-millimeter
zoom and the background was very distracting

00:12:04.720 --> 00:12:06.700
so I'm
shooting at a wide aperture.

00:12:06.700 --> 00:12:11.220
I'm shooting at a wide
aperture to blur the background.

00:12:11.220 --> 00:12:14.400
In wildlife
photography and in people photography, I do

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:16.450
the same
thing when I find a subject.

00:12:16.450 --> 00:12:20.010
I take what's called the
environmental shot -- these are nesting albatrosses

00:12:20.010 --> 00:12:22.870
on
Diego Ramirez Island -- I like to take what's

00:12:22.870 --> 00:12:24.380
called the
environmental shot.

00:12:24.380 --> 00:12:28.950
The subject in the environment, and
then I like to go in and take the closeup

00:12:28.950 --> 00:12:30.800
so I'm telling
the story.

00:12:30.800 --> 00:12:34.440
I don't know what shot I'm going to like
best later, I don't know which one someone

00:12:34.440 --> 00:12:37.570
may buy, but
if you do it both ways, again, and having

00:12:37.570 --> 00:12:41.650
those two
cameras lets you shoot fast, you'll have what

00:12:41.650 --> 00:12:45.000
you need.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:48.620
So when you shoot a subject with a lot of
white in it,

00:12:48.620 --> 00:12:52.330
this is going to sound backwards, too.

00:12:52.330 --> 00:12:53.330
Yes.

00:12:53.330 --> 00:12:56.210
[Asking
question in the background]

00:12:56.210 --> 00:12:59.620
&gt;&gt;RICK: Why did I chop the legs?

00:12:59.620 --> 00:13:02.670
It looks like
I chopped the legs, but he's actually -- she

00:13:02.670 --> 00:13:05.120
is actually
sitting on a nest.

00:13:05.120 --> 00:13:07.210
So these are nesting albatrosses.

00:13:07.210 --> 00:13:08.210
Okay?

00:13:08.210 --> 00:13:10.530
So they have their nests in these little mud
--

00:13:10.530 --> 00:13:13.760
mud piles here, so from back there it may
look like

00:13:13.760 --> 00:13:17.400
that, but they're actually sitting on the
nest but you

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:18.400
have a good eye.

00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:23.090
So anyway, if there's a lot of white
in the picture, like here, you want to -- if

00:13:23.090 --> 00:13:25.340
you're
shooting on automatic, you want to set your

00:13:25.340 --> 00:13:28.730
camera on
plus one as a starting point.

00:13:28.730 --> 00:13:29.920
But, this may sound
backward.

00:13:29.920 --> 00:13:31.420
You know you know, hey, there's all this
light.

00:13:31.420 --> 00:13:32.420
It's so bright.

00:13:32.420 --> 00:13:34.680
I want to set my camera on plus
one?

00:13:34.680 --> 00:13:35.930
Well, you do.

00:13:35.930 --> 00:13:40.550
Because all that light, all that
bright area, fools the camera's exposure meter

00:13:40.550 --> 00:13:42.880
into
thinking the scene is brighter than it actually

00:13:42.880 --> 00:13:45.860
is and
will underexpose your picture.

00:13:45.860 --> 00:13:48.840
I shoot all my pictures,
except my flash pictures -- as you'll see

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:51.880
in the studio
later when we move over there with Cliff -- I

00:13:51.880 --> 00:13:55.370
shoot
either on the aperture priority mode or the

00:13:55.370 --> 00:13:57.100
shutter
priority mode.

00:13:57.100 --> 00:14:01.090
A lot of my professional photographer
friends shoot on the aperture priority mode

00:14:01.090 --> 00:14:03.040
or the
shutter priority mode.

00:14:03.040 --> 00:14:06.710
If you think about it, there's
only one right exposure; right?

00:14:06.710 --> 00:14:09.630
And if you use manual
or aperture priority, or shutter priority,

00:14:09.630 --> 00:14:10.740
it doesn't
matter.

00:14:10.740 --> 00:14:15.540
I found since I've been shooting a long time
that I can just use the exposure compensation

00:14:15.540 --> 00:14:19.190
wheel on
my camera to dial in the right exposure very

00:14:19.190 --> 00:14:20.190
quickly.

00:14:20.190 --> 00:14:22.350
And in a case like this, a case like this,
a case like

00:14:22.350 --> 00:14:26.110
this, case like this, the depth of field is
the most

00:14:26.110 --> 00:14:27.110
important thing.

00:14:27.110 --> 00:14:30.400
So why not shoot on the aperture
priority mode?

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:35.810
Set your aperture and then as the light
level changes, the camera will automatically

00:14:35.810 --> 00:14:38.520
pick the
correct shutter speed for the existing situation.

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:39.520
Yes?

00:14:39.520 --> 00:14:41.080
&gt;&gt; Male #1: What metering mode do you use?

00:14:41.080 --> 00:14:44.510
&gt;&gt;RICK: What metering mode do I use?

00:14:44.510 --> 00:14:48.960
I use the
evaluative metering mode and here's why because

00:14:48.960 --> 00:14:53.230
I can
look at a scene like this and say okay, I'm

00:14:53.230 --> 00:14:56.490
just going
to set this at evaluative metering.

00:14:56.490 --> 00:14:59.700
If I just left it
on zero exposure compensation setting these

00:14:59.700 --> 00:15:01.500
birds would
be a little washed out.

00:15:01.500 --> 00:15:04.550
They look a little washed out
here, they're fine on the screen here.

00:15:04.550 --> 00:15:05.550
Okay?

00:15:05.550 --> 00:15:07.600
So
knowing that, that all this dark area would

00:15:07.600 --> 00:15:11.370
fool the
camera's meter into thinking the scene has

00:15:11.370 --> 00:15:14.560
all this dark
in it and no white, I have to underexpose

00:15:14.560 --> 00:15:15.820
a little in
camera.

00:15:15.820 --> 00:15:17.950
So I'm setting my exposure compensation for
a

00:15:17.950 --> 00:15:22.010
scene like this a little under, make a third
under.

00:15:22.010 --> 00:15:25.710
The
key in all photography is learning how to

00:15:25.710 --> 00:15:26.710
see the light.

00:15:26.710 --> 00:15:29.210
If you learn how to seen the light, then you
know how

00:15:29.210 --> 00:15:32.270
you can make adjustments on your camera, knowing
again

00:15:32.270 --> 00:15:36.570
that there's only white -- one right exposure
for you.

00:15:36.570 --> 00:15:39.510
So in seeing the light, it's all about this.

00:15:39.510 --> 00:15:42.070
It's first
seeing the contrast range in the scene.

00:15:42.070 --> 00:15:44.610
There's not a
lot of contrast in the scene, so here we don't

00:15:44.610 --> 00:15:48.610
have to
make that many adjustments exposure wise.

00:15:48.610 --> 00:15:49.610
Right?

00:15:49.610 --> 00:15:51.740
So we
have to learn to see the contrast range in

00:15:51.740 --> 00:15:55.400
the scene; we
have to learn to see the direction of light;

00:15:55.400 --> 00:15:57.970
we have to
learn how to see the quality of light, hard

00:15:57.970 --> 00:16:00.420
or soft,
it's soft; and then we have to learn -- what's

00:16:00.420 --> 00:16:02.590
the other
thing about light?

00:16:02.590 --> 00:16:04.060
Color.

00:16:04.060 --> 00:16:07.480
So we have to learn how to
see the contrast range in the scene, the quality

00:16:07.480 --> 00:16:10.320
of
light, the direction of light, and the color

00:16:10.320 --> 00:16:11.320
of light.

00:16:11.320 --> 00:16:13.770
Once we learn how to the light, then we can
make the

00:16:13.770 --> 00:16:17.000
right adjustments with the -- inside our camera,
or add

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:20.570
a flash, use a reflector or diffuser, wait
for a

00:16:20.570 --> 00:16:23.820
different time of day,, and then after we
do that on

00:16:23.820 --> 00:16:26.550
site, then we can go into the digital darkroom
and work

00:16:26.550 --> 00:16:27.850
and play with the light.

00:16:27.850 --> 00:16:31.320
If you think about it, every
picture I'm going to show you right here has

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:35.670
exactly the
same main element, and that's light.

00:16:35.670 --> 00:16:39.630
So it's very, very
important to learn how to see the light, then

00:16:39.630 --> 00:16:41.580
learn how
to control the light, and we'll be talking

00:16:41.580 --> 00:16:45.840
about that
more a little in the presentation.

00:16:45.840 --> 00:16:49.240
One of my
photography tips -- one of my famous one-liners

00:16:49.240 --> 00:16:52.110
is
"The name of the game is to fill the frame."

00:16:52.110 --> 00:16:53.540
I like to
shoot tight.

00:16:53.540 --> 00:16:57.100
I like -- like here, I like to fill the
frame with the subject, yet there is something

00:16:57.100 --> 00:17:00.589
to be
said for negative space, for dead space.

00:17:00.589 --> 00:17:04.770
So when I give
you these tips, try them and try actually

00:17:04.770 --> 00:17:06.990
the total
opposite of them.

00:17:06.990 --> 00:17:10.329
But most -- we were talking about
this before when we sat down.

00:17:10.329 --> 00:17:14.189
When you're photographing
a person, when you think you're close, get

00:17:14.189 --> 00:17:16.669
closer; when
you're photographing an animal, a building,

00:17:16.669 --> 00:17:18.720
when you
think you're close, get closer.

00:17:18.720 --> 00:17:23.079
And cropping doesn't
bring you closer, but it emphasizes the subject

00:17:23.079 --> 00:17:24.919
a lot --
a lot more.

00:17:24.919 --> 00:17:29.029
This is a very basic tip, but I shoot
everything vertically, I shoot everything

00:17:29.029 --> 00:17:30.100
horizontally.

00:17:30.100 --> 00:17:32.559
Again,on what I'm going to like, I don't know
what

00:17:32.559 --> 00:17:34.870
someone else is going to like who might want
to buy the

00:17:34.870 --> 00:17:35.980
picture.

00:17:35.980 --> 00:17:40.409
If I'm going to offer the picture to a
magazine, I don't know whether they have space

00:17:40.409 --> 00:17:41.940
for a
horizontal or a vertical.

00:17:41.940 --> 00:17:44.799
Again, a very basic tip, but
I do that.

00:17:44.799 --> 00:17:48.139
Again, here are some monochromatic images.

00:17:48.139 --> 00:17:51.440
If the pictures don't have a lot of color,
I'm going to

00:17:51.440 --> 00:17:53.769
make them black and white.

00:17:53.769 --> 00:17:56.299
And when I go somewhere, I'm
trying to tell the story.

00:17:56.299 --> 00:18:00.269
I'm thinking as a magazine
photographer; I'm thinking if I'm putting

00:18:00.269 --> 00:18:02.340
a slide show
together.

00:18:02.340 --> 00:18:05.649
So this would make a nice ending picture for
a slide show.

00:18:05.649 --> 00:18:09.499
Try to tell the story, just don't go to
Antarctica or wherever and say okay, I'm going

00:18:09.499 --> 00:18:12.240
to take a
lot of closeup pictures of this or that.

00:18:12.240 --> 00:18:16.580
Try to tell
the story of wherever you go.

00:18:16.580 --> 00:18:17.950
So the first trip was
amazing.

00:18:17.950 --> 00:18:20.580
I had an unbelievable time.

00:18:20.580 --> 00:18:24.000
The people liked
me teaching so they said hey, could you come

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:25.000
back?

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:26.950
So
two years ago they asked me to come back.

00:18:26.950 --> 00:18:31.539
Now this --
this was a special trip to photograph the

00:18:31.539 --> 00:18:33.179
emperor
penguins.

00:18:33.179 --> 00:18:35.250
People save up their whole lives.

00:18:35.250 --> 00:18:37.779
On their
life list they want to photograph the emperor

00:18:37.779 --> 00:18:38.779
penguins.

00:18:38.779 --> 00:18:41.059
The penguins are about this high, they're
in remote

00:18:41.059 --> 00:18:44.999
colonies, but they are magnificent, magnificent
animals

00:18:44.999 --> 00:18:47.789
so they needed a pro.

00:18:47.789 --> 00:18:49.049
So I said "Sure, I'll go."

00:18:49.049 --> 00:18:52.889
So the company hired me,
but this is a very short trip.

00:18:52.889 --> 00:18:57.299
It was a 12-day trip -- not
counting getting there, okay, which is like

00:18:57.299 --> 00:19:03.480
a day, and
coming It's three days going over the Drake's

00:19:03.480 --> 00:19:06.640
Passage, which
can be the roughest seas in the world, right,

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:10.620
three days
returning, only six days of shooting.

00:19:10.620 --> 00:19:14.980
So this is a big
investment for just six days of shooting.

00:19:14.980 --> 00:19:17.769
Again, this
is a lifelong dream for people.

00:19:17.769 --> 00:19:21.780
So we leave Ushuaia,
the sky is great, it was sunny, people are

00:19:21.780 --> 00:19:24.149
cheering,
we're having champagne on the bow of the boat,

00:19:24.149 --> 00:19:26.679
the
stern, all the way around the rail.

00:19:26.679 --> 00:19:28.530
It was amazing
going there.

00:19:28.530 --> 00:19:32.720
So we're getting closer to Antarctica,
we're getting closer to this emperor penguin

00:19:32.720 --> 00:19:33.890
colony.

00:19:33.890 --> 00:19:36.169
This is called pancake ice.

00:19:36.169 --> 00:19:37.169
We start seeing this.

00:19:37.169 --> 00:19:38.919
We
see our first tiny little penguin, you can

00:19:38.919 --> 00:19:40.049
see him up
here.

00:19:40.049 --> 00:19:41.619
People are cheering hey, we're getting closer
to

00:19:41.619 --> 00:19:42.720
the colony.

00:19:42.720 --> 00:19:46.760
Now, this was really like a National
Geographic expedition.

00:19:46.760 --> 00:19:50.440
We're in this Russian ice
breaker and it's going through the ice, the

00:19:50.440 --> 00:19:53.860
ice is,
like, smashing off the bow at night when we

00:19:53.860 --> 00:19:54.860
were
sleeping.

00:19:54.860 --> 00:19:57.649
It was so noisy that you really felt that
you

00:19:57.649 --> 00:19:59.830
were on an expedition.

00:19:59.830 --> 00:20:02.710
One of my photography tips in
addition to the name of the game is to fill

00:20:02.710 --> 00:20:05.559
the frame is
to always look back.

00:20:05.559 --> 00:20:09.320
Everyone's on the bow, here's the
bow crashing through the ice, but I like to

00:20:09.320 --> 00:20:10.879
look back.

00:20:10.879 --> 00:20:14.520
Always look up, always look down, always look
back;

00:20:14.520 --> 00:20:16.889
This'll open up a whole new world of photo
opportunities

00:20:16.889 --> 00:20:17.889
for you.

00:20:17.889 --> 00:20:22.750
So here I look back and I see the path that
this ice breaker is just breaking through

00:20:22.750 --> 00:20:24.009
the ice.

00:20:24.009 --> 00:20:26.740
So
we get to Antarctica, the ice is so thick

00:20:26.740 --> 00:20:31.659
now the boat
is moving really slow, again, the ice is crashing

00:20:31.659 --> 00:20:33.090
all
around.

00:20:33.090 --> 00:20:38.009
The night before -- after three days of
traveling, all right, we get to Antarctica

00:20:38.009 --> 00:20:40.649
the night
before they bring out these two Russian-made

00:20:40.649 --> 00:20:41.649
helicopters.

00:20:41.649 --> 00:20:43.230
Russian ice breaker, Russian helicopters.

00:20:43.230 --> 00:20:46.110
How cool is this if you want to talk about
being on an

00:20:46.110 --> 00:20:47.200
expedition?

00:20:47.200 --> 00:20:50.690
So they bring them out to test them --
they're bringing them out to test them because

00:20:50.690 --> 00:20:53.299
we're
going to fly over to the emperor penguin colony

00:20:53.299 --> 00:20:56.100
because
the ship can't get close.

00:20:56.100 --> 00:20:59.250
So they bring them out and it
starts to get overcast.

00:20:59.250 --> 00:21:03.539
Now, although there is no such
thing as a bad day for pictures, everyone,

00:21:03.539 --> 00:21:06.639
you know,
they wanted that bright sunlight, they wanted

00:21:06.639 --> 00:21:10.049
the blue
sky, the penguins against the blue sky, and

00:21:10.049 --> 00:21:13.470
also it was
a lot warmer when the sun comes out.

00:21:13.470 --> 00:21:16.419
So the captain
says -- he gets on the PA system and he says,

00:21:16.419 --> 00:21:18.249
I don't
know if we're going to be able to go tomorrow

00:21:18.249 --> 00:21:22.480
after
three days on the ship, after one day of trying

00:21:22.480 --> 00:21:23.940
to get
there.

00:21:23.940 --> 00:21:27.720
So we go in, have dinner, we come out after
dinner, and the sun comes out.

00:21:27.720 --> 00:21:30.341
So everyone's like
really happy and saying I can't believe it.

00:21:30.341 --> 00:21:31.460
This is
going to be great.

00:21:31.460 --> 00:21:35.700
We go back inside and I'm teaching
photography, I'm teaching Photoshop, light

00:21:35.700 --> 00:21:37.230
room,
teaching all this stuff, getting everyone's

00:21:37.230 --> 00:21:38.850
cameras set
up.

00:21:38.850 --> 00:21:41.540
We wake up the next morning, and this is what
it

00:21:41.540 --> 00:21:42.540
looked like.

00:21:42.540 --> 00:21:44.140
It was totally overcast.

00:21:44.140 --> 00:21:47.419
Captain gets on
the PA and says, sorry, we're not going anywhere.

00:21:47.419 --> 00:21:49.330
So
this is day one.

00:21:49.330 --> 00:21:51.809
Well, on day two to four it snowed.

00:21:51.809 --> 00:21:53.389
[Laughing]
&gt;&gt;RICK: So we couldn't.

00:21:53.389 --> 00:21:57.539
So we're stuck on the
ship and this was, again, a lifelong dream

00:21:57.539 --> 00:21:58.600
for people.

00:21:58.600 --> 00:21:59.600
But it got worse.

00:21:59.600 --> 00:22:04.739
Half the ship, including me, got
what's called the Norwalk virus, and the Norwalk

00:22:04.739 --> 00:22:07.279
virus
is -- he's laughing so I guess you know what

00:22:07.279 --> 00:22:08.279
it is.

00:22:08.279 --> 00:22:10.259
It's the most -- it's like the worst virus
you

00:22:10.259 --> 00:22:11.259
could possibly get.

00:22:11.259 --> 00:22:12.289
You feel like you're going to die.

00:22:12.289 --> 00:22:14.770
I was calling Susan on the ship's phone, I
was telling

00:22:14.770 --> 00:22:17.169
her where the will is and stuff like this
because I

00:22:17.169 --> 00:22:18.590
really thought I was gonna die.

00:22:18.590 --> 00:22:19.759
It's so bad.

00:22:19.759 --> 00:22:22.039
So
this is day two to four.

00:22:22.039 --> 00:22:25.119
So on day five I figured I
have to get off this ship.

00:22:25.119 --> 00:22:28.890
I just have to get off this
ship so I'm taking some snapshots just walking

00:22:28.890 --> 00:22:29.970
around
the ship.

00:22:29.970 --> 00:22:34.809
And by the way, as the pro, they don't give
you -- they don't give you the best cabin.

00:22:34.809 --> 00:22:37.549
My cabin was
way up on the top left there.

00:22:37.549 --> 00:22:41.139
They give the crew the
top cabins so when the boat swings like this,

00:22:41.139 --> 00:22:45.470
you know,
we get the severest cases of being seasick.

00:22:45.470 --> 00:22:49.830
So anyway,
on day six, the last day, there was a mutiny.

00:22:49.830 --> 00:22:53.440
The
guests -- we got together actually in a theater

00:22:53.440 --> 00:22:55.830
like
this, and the guests said, we paid all this

00:22:55.830 --> 00:22:56.830
money; we
want to go.

00:22:56.830 --> 00:22:59.190
So the captain said okay, if you want to
go, we'll go.

00:22:59.190 --> 00:23:03.409
So we get over -- we get in the
helicopters, he's flying us over, but here's

00:23:03.409 --> 00:23:04.799
the thing.

00:23:04.799 --> 00:23:08.799
We couldn't land closer than 2 miles -- 2
miles to the

00:23:08.799 --> 00:23:11.299
emperor penguin colony because they didn't
want to scare

00:23:11.299 --> 00:23:14.369
the penguins with the helicopters.

00:23:14.369 --> 00:23:17.129
So with all this
gear -- I have a 40-pound backpack -- Cliff,

00:23:17.129 --> 00:23:20.600
you'll see
most of the gear that I have this afternoon

00:23:20.600 --> 00:23:22.650
--
forty-pound backpack, I've been sick, the

00:23:22.650 --> 00:23:25.740
guests have
been sick for all these days, we walk over

00:23:25.740 --> 00:23:28.139
the ice with
our life jackets because you're on ice so

00:23:28.139 --> 00:23:29.860
they set up
this camp there.

00:23:29.860 --> 00:23:33.620
So we're getting closer to the emperor
penguin colony and it was really cool seeing

00:23:33.620 --> 00:23:35.299
these
emperor penguins.

00:23:35.299 --> 00:23:36.789
This is how big they are.

00:23:36.789 --> 00:23:39.059
And the
thing is, they're not -- they're not hunted,

00:23:39.059 --> 00:23:41.369
so you can
get very close to these animals just like

00:23:41.369 --> 00:23:44.970
in Galapagos
you can get very close to the animals in Galapagos

00:23:44.970 --> 00:23:47.720
because they're not hunted.

00:23:47.720 --> 00:23:51.070
So this is one shot that I
took, kind of like this.

00:23:51.070 --> 00:23:52.700
This is called "Babysitting",
right.

00:23:52.700 --> 00:23:58.419
It's the adult -- it's the mama emperor penguin
with the chicks, and this is the other.

00:23:58.419 --> 00:24:03.019
You've probably
seen pictures like this on National Geographic.

00:24:03.019 --> 00:24:06.700
Beautiful blue sky, the parents, the chick,
the

00:24:06.700 --> 00:24:09.710
background's out of focus, nice framing.

00:24:09.710 --> 00:24:13.230
Well, this
isn't the original shot; this is the original

00:24:13.230 --> 00:24:14.230
shot.

00:24:14.230 --> 00:24:17.009
As
a travel photographer, if a photojournalist

00:24:17.009 --> 00:24:20.399
was there,
he or she would publish this type of picture,

00:24:20.399 --> 00:24:22.690
but
because I'm a travel photographer, I have

00:24:22.690 --> 00:24:24.879
the license to
enhance my pictures.

00:24:24.879 --> 00:24:31.389
So what I did is I just added the
gradual filter and increased the contrast

00:24:31.389 --> 00:24:32.389
and
saturation.

00:24:32.389 --> 00:24:36.239
But if there's ever a magazine published
called National Adventure and they want an

00:24:36.239 --> 00:24:39.669
article
Rick's Trip from Hell believe me -- believe

00:24:39.669 --> 00:24:42.240
me, I am
ready to write this article.

00:24:42.240 --> 00:24:46.690
And the article would
actually be called this: "The Safety of Reminiscence."

00:24:46.690 --> 00:24:50.320
Marco Polo had a wonderful saying and the
saying is "An

00:24:50.320 --> 00:24:53.159
adventure is misery and discomfort... relived
in the

00:24:53.159 --> 00:24:54.789
safety of reminiscence."

00:24:54.789 --> 00:24:57.570
like here we're laughing about
this, I'm having a good time, I hope you're

00:24:57.570 --> 00:24:59.519
having a
good time, right?

00:24:59.519 --> 00:25:03.179
But again I felt like I was going to
die.

00:25:03.179 --> 00:25:06.639
On a more serious note, the most important
thing

00:25:06.639 --> 00:25:11.059
that we can do in our photography, I think,
is buy a

00:25:11.059 --> 00:25:12.059
camera -- no.

00:25:12.059 --> 00:25:14.289
[chuckles] The most important thing that we
can do I

00:25:14.289 --> 00:25:16.190
think is set a goal.

00:25:16.190 --> 00:25:18.299
Setting goals is so important.

00:25:18.299 --> 00:25:19.960
I
used to tell my son -- Susan and I would tell

00:25:19.960 --> 00:25:22.269
my son
this all the time.

00:25:22.269 --> 00:25:25.610
He set the goal to be the
valedictorian in high school; he achieved

00:25:25.610 --> 00:25:26.610
that goal.

00:25:26.610 --> 00:25:28.409
You guys are working at Google here.

00:25:28.409 --> 00:25:31.940
You set the goal
to get a job at Google; obviously it worked.

00:25:31.940 --> 00:25:34.830
In
photography -- in life and in photography

00:25:34.830 --> 00:25:37.070
we must set
goals.

00:25:37.070 --> 00:25:42.269
I was teaching a workshop up in Alaska
photographing bald eagles and I was on the

00:25:42.269 --> 00:25:44.690
back of a
boat -- and actually it's a funny story.

00:25:44.690 --> 00:25:48.200
I was in the
back of a boat hand-holding my Canon with

00:25:48.200 --> 00:25:52.090
a 70 to 200
millimeter F4 lens, which is less expensive

00:25:52.090 --> 00:25:55.239
than the 70
to 200 2A lens.

00:25:55.239 --> 00:26:01.279
I'm hand holding this and there's guys
on the back of the boat with $11,000 400-millimeter

00:26:01.279 --> 00:26:04.259
setups with the 400-millimeter 2A lens and
the super

00:26:04.259 --> 00:26:07.529
body and all this stuff, and I'm hand holding
shots.

00:26:07.529 --> 00:26:10.820
You don't need the world's best gear to get
pretty nice

00:26:10.820 --> 00:26:11.820
shots.

00:26:11.820 --> 00:26:12.960
If the lights were a little darker, you'd
see

00:26:12.960 --> 00:26:14.320
that this picture really pops.

00:26:14.320 --> 00:26:17.659
But anyway, we're on the
back of the boat and guys are shooting the

00:26:17.659 --> 00:26:19.919
eagles coming
down, shooting the eagles coming up, catching

00:26:19.919 --> 00:26:23.100
the fish,
and I have all these pictures here, but one

00:26:23.100 --> 00:26:25.539
morning I
set the goal to get the shot.

00:26:25.539 --> 00:26:27.429
This is the one shot I
really wanted to get.

00:26:27.429 --> 00:26:32.159
I wanted to get a symmetrical
shot of the eagle coming in to catch a fish

00:26:32.159 --> 00:26:34.059
with the
perfect reflection here.

00:26:34.059 --> 00:26:35.299
So I set that goal.

00:26:35.299 --> 00:26:36.730
So what
did I have to do?

00:26:36.730 --> 00:26:42.179
I knew I had to use a fast shutter
speed, I knew I had to set my exposure -- underexposure

00:26:42.179 --> 00:26:44.470
just -- underexposing just a little so the
white

00:26:44.470 --> 00:26:47.239
feathers weren't all overexposed.

00:26:47.239 --> 00:26:49.889
This is actually the
hardest subject I've ever photographed because

00:26:49.889 --> 00:26:52.929
the
animal's moving fast and you have really dark

00:26:52.929 --> 00:26:56.259
feathers
and dark background against really bright

00:26:56.259 --> 00:26:57.259
feathers
here.

00:26:57.259 --> 00:27:00.639
So anyway, I had to use rapid frame advance;
set

00:27:00.639 --> 00:27:04.350
the exposure right; use AI servo focus, which
is like

00:27:04.350 --> 00:27:07.399
focus tracking, it tracks the subject; and
I had to

00:27:07.399 --> 00:27:09.539
focus on a specific area.

00:27:09.539 --> 00:27:13.629
And we actually had the
captain move to boat to an area where we had

00:27:13.629 --> 00:27:15.409
beautiful
reflections.

00:27:15.409 --> 00:27:17.600
We set the goal, I got the shot.

00:27:17.600 --> 00:27:20.990
So in
your photography it's very, very important

00:27:20.990 --> 00:27:22.419
to set a
specific goals.

00:27:22.419 --> 00:27:26.340
If you go up to Alaska on a trip, it's
not a goal I'm going to get great shots of

00:27:26.340 --> 00:27:27.340
bald eagles.

00:27:27.340 --> 00:27:29.619
I'm going to get a shot of the eagle with
the talons

00:27:29.619 --> 00:27:30.619
coming out.

00:27:30.619 --> 00:27:34.919
I'm going to get the shot of an eagle, in
one second, of just catching the fish.

00:27:34.919 --> 00:27:37.809
I'm going to get
a shot of the eagle taking off after it just

00:27:37.809 --> 00:27:38.809
caught a
fish.

00:27:38.809 --> 00:27:41.289
I'm going to get a nice action shot like this.

00:27:41.289 --> 00:27:42.289
I'm going to shoot up.

00:27:42.289 --> 00:27:43.580
I'm going to shoot down.

00:27:43.580 --> 00:27:45.590
I'm
going to shoot all around.

00:27:45.590 --> 00:27:48.820
If you make like a hit list,
again, set that goal.

00:27:48.820 --> 00:27:50.450
You'll know where you're going.

00:27:50.450 --> 00:27:51.450
Yes?

00:27:51.450 --> 00:27:54.139
&gt;&gt; Female #2: So when you were photos of the
eagle, were you

00:27:54.139 --> 00:27:57.090
focusing on the white part on the eagle's
head or the

00:27:57.090 --> 00:27:59.539
darkest--
&gt;&gt;RICK: I was focusing on the body because

00:27:59.539 --> 00:28:01.049
it's
a very small point.

00:28:01.049 --> 00:28:05.860
So I'm actually using the center
focus point on my camera even though my camera

00:28:05.860 --> 00:28:09.279
has 45
autofocus points -- you know, these cameras

00:28:09.279 --> 00:28:12.000
today have
all these different focus points -- I'm using

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:15.429
that AI
servo focus and I want to focus right -- like

00:28:15.429 --> 00:28:18.100
here, like
right on the animal's body.

00:28:18.100 --> 00:28:21.350
But talking about animal --
these shots, if you look at all these shots

00:28:21.350 --> 00:28:23.139
they have
something in common.

00:28:23.139 --> 00:28:29.309
When I'm photographing animals and
people in most cases if the eye is not in

00:28:29.309 --> 00:28:32.859
focus, if the
eye's not well lit, I feel I've missed the

00:28:32.859 --> 00:28:34.789
shot.

00:28:34.789 --> 00:28:36.019
That's
what I strive for.

00:28:36.019 --> 00:28:40.259
The reason I say most people
photography, if Marlon Brando was here and

00:28:40.259 --> 00:28:43.710
he said hey,
Marlon Brando -- it's really fun to be at

00:28:43.710 --> 00:28:47.119
Google -- --
he'd say well, Rick, most of the times that's

00:28:47.119 --> 00:28:48.119
true.

00:28:48.119 --> 00:28:49.899
But
you might remember when I shot the Godfather

00:28:49.899 --> 00:28:51.529
I used top
lighting.

00:28:51.529 --> 00:28:53.570
I used top lighting so the people looking
at

00:28:53.570 --> 00:28:56.419
the movie couldn't see into the subject's
eyes because I

00:28:56.419 --> 00:28:58.899
wanted to create a sense of mystery.

00:28:58.899 --> 00:29:01.440
I'm sure,
Katherine, you like the eyes most of the time.

00:29:01.440 --> 00:29:04.080
It's
very important in portraiture and wedding

00:29:04.080 --> 00:29:06.679
photographer -- wedding photography to light
the eyes;

00:29:06.679 --> 00:29:07.679
right?

00:29:07.679 --> 00:29:08.679
Okay.

00:29:08.679 --> 00:29:11.639
So anyway, that's the thing in wildlife
photography.

00:29:11.639 --> 00:29:12.820
So what do we do?

00:29:12.820 --> 00:29:15.970
We're actually
positioning the boat so we have good light

00:29:15.970 --> 00:29:19.220
on the
animals' eyes.

00:29:19.220 --> 00:29:23.710
I was talking -- I was giving a talk
down at the California Photo Fest last week

00:29:23.710 --> 00:29:26.460
and it was
on composition.

00:29:26.460 --> 00:29:31.970
How many people here have heard the
composition technique the Rule of Thirds?

00:29:31.970 --> 00:29:32.970
Okay.

00:29:32.970 --> 00:29:33.970
Just
about everybody.

00:29:33.970 --> 00:29:37.840
How many people have heard the
composition technique Rule of Odds?

00:29:37.840 --> 00:29:39.210
Nobody.

00:29:39.210 --> 00:29:42.039
The Rule
of Odds is actually a very good composition

00:29:42.039 --> 00:29:43.039
technique.

00:29:43.039 --> 00:29:45.580
You put odd things in a picture, they're going
to stand

00:29:45.580 --> 00:29:46.730
out.

00:29:46.730 --> 00:29:49.100
You put, you know, even things, they don't
stand

00:29:49.100 --> 00:29:50.679
out as much for whatever reason.

00:29:50.679 --> 00:29:55.009
So this has three
dolphins in here -- actually whales before

00:29:55.009 --> 00:29:58.039
rather
than -- and then four.

00:29:58.039 --> 00:30:01.960
So I had a lot of pictures with
four in them, but I liked the shot with the

00:30:01.960 --> 00:30:02.960
three.

00:30:02.960 --> 00:30:04.229
I
was thinking about that composition technique,

00:30:04.229 --> 00:30:05.989
the Rule
of Odds.

00:30:05.989 --> 00:30:10.609
Simplicity is really important, too so right
here we have just one animal.

00:30:10.609 --> 00:30:12.830
Now, I have these
beautiful patterns here.

00:30:12.830 --> 00:30:16.129
I'm using that polarizing
filter that we were talking about before to

00:30:16.129 --> 00:30:18.399
cut through
the glare on the water.

00:30:18.399 --> 00:30:22.909
If you're shooting in water,
around water, over water, next to water, you

00:30:22.909 --> 00:30:24.230
want to
bring a polarizing filter.

00:30:24.230 --> 00:30:25.230
Yes?

00:30:25.230 --> 00:30:26.230
&gt;&gt; Female #3: Do you like a circular polarizer
or do you just

00:30:26.230 --> 00:30:27.230
like the sheet for a polarizer?

00:30:27.230 --> 00:30:32.399
&gt;&gt; RICK: Well, the circular -- we used to
have

00:30:32.399 --> 00:30:35.019
what's called the linear polarizing filter
before you

00:30:35.019 --> 00:30:36.889
probably got into photography.

00:30:36.889 --> 00:30:40.120
Now they had to develop
what's called circular polarizing filters

00:30:40.120 --> 00:30:42.820
for the
autofocus cameras; the linear polarizing filters

00:30:42.820 --> 00:30:43.880
didn't
work.

00:30:43.880 --> 00:30:45.870
But I -- that's what I use.

00:30:45.870 --> 00:30:49.649
I like to use the
circular polarizing filters.

00:30:49.649 --> 00:30:51.510
And again telling the
story.

00:30:51.510 --> 00:30:53.759
I'm trying to tell the whole story of the
whale

00:30:53.759 --> 00:30:55.899
so I'm doing the whale's tail.

00:30:55.899 --> 00:30:59.149
This picture might look
a little confusing, but what's going on here

00:30:59.149 --> 00:31:00.360
is I was
pretty lucky.

00:31:00.360 --> 00:31:02.580
These whales come up and they were eating
the krill.

00:31:02.580 --> 00:31:07.169
The reason it looks kind of weird is because
the jaws come -- they distend and they like

00:31:07.169 --> 00:31:09.759
open like
this to the side so they can get the maximum

00:31:09.759 --> 00:31:11.320
amount of
krill.

00:31:11.320 --> 00:31:12.629
It's pretty cool.

00:31:12.629 --> 00:31:15.669
Again, telling the story, watching the background.

00:31:15.669 --> 00:31:17.749
You know, if I took -- this picture could
have been

00:31:17.749 --> 00:31:21.059
taken off Long Island not too far from my
house.

00:31:21.059 --> 00:31:24.010
This
picture looks like it was taken in Alaska.

00:31:24.010 --> 00:31:26.779
We want to
take pictures that have what's called a sense

00:31:26.779 --> 00:31:27.779
of place.

00:31:27.779 --> 00:31:30.690
This picture's nice, this picture's nice;
the closeups,

00:31:30.690 --> 00:31:33.239
they're nice, but they could have been taken
anywhere.

00:31:33.239 --> 00:31:35.759
. So think about that when you're taking pictures.

00:31:35.759 --> 00:31:38.609
Think
about how can I take a picture that has a

00:31:38.609 --> 00:31:41.159
sense of
place?

00:31:41.159 --> 00:31:45.860
Another tip I want to share with you I learned
from my friend Dr. Dick Zakia, he where to

00:31:45.860 --> 00:31:48.279
wonderful
book called "Perception and Imaging".

00:31:48.279 --> 00:31:52.049
"Perception and
Imaging", Dr. Dick Zakia.

00:31:52.049 --> 00:31:54.309
In that book he has nothing
about F-stops and shutter speeds.

00:31:54.309 --> 00:31:58.129
It's all about -- or
raw, or JPEGs, or image sensors, or anything

00:31:58.129 --> 00:31:59.129
like that.

00:31:59.129 --> 00:32:00.919
It's all about -- what he talks about -- what
he talks

00:32:00.919 --> 00:32:04.110
about is why we like pictures, the perception,
and how

00:32:04.110 --> 00:32:05.510
it relates to imaging.

00:32:05.510 --> 00:32:10.330
But one of his best tips is use
your camera like a spaceship.

00:32:10.330 --> 00:32:11.759
I teach a lot of
workshops.

00:32:11.759 --> 00:32:16.570
We were doing a workshop last week down at
the pier, the pier in San Luis Obispo actually,

00:32:16.570 --> 00:32:19.919
I
forget, in Cayucos, not too far from San Luis

00:32:19.919 --> 00:32:21.039
Obispo.

00:32:21.039 --> 00:32:22.889
Everyone shows up with their tripods and their
cameras

00:32:22.889 --> 00:32:24.419
are like this at eye level.

00:32:24.419 --> 00:32:27.749
When you start using your
camera like a spaceship, you could come up

00:32:27.749 --> 00:32:30.539
with all new different
composition techniques.

00:32:30.539 --> 00:32:34.249
Here I'm on the back of the
boat, I'm holding my camera probably about

00:32:34.249 --> 00:32:37.460
6 inches
above the water with the [chuckles] strap

00:32:37.460 --> 00:32:39.399
on to make sure I didn't
lose it.

00:32:39.399 --> 00:32:43.539
But I wanted to have this feeling of speed
that our boat is like cruising up through

00:32:43.539 --> 00:32:44.669
the water up
in Alaska.

00:32:44.669 --> 00:32:48.960
If I was up like this, it wouldn't have the
same effect.

00:32:48.960 --> 00:32:53.620
So use your camera like a spaceship; tilt
it up; tilt it down; tilt it to the left;

00:32:53.620 --> 00:32:54.620
tilt it to the
right.

00:32:54.620 --> 00:32:57.919
If you think about that spaceship technique,
you'll see that you that you will come up

00:32:57.919 --> 00:32:59.739
with different
pictures.

00:32:59.739 --> 00:33:04.169
As far as the composition technique, another
one, leading lines.

00:33:04.169 --> 00:33:07.779
Here we have these leading lines or
leading shapes that are leading the viewer

00:33:07.779 --> 00:33:10.649
right up to
this mountain in the back.

00:33:10.649 --> 00:33:12.330
There are a million
different composition techniques.

00:33:12.330 --> 00:33:16.200
I only have time
really to share a few with you with you, but

00:33:16.200 --> 00:33:19.639
contours,
contours are another form of composition.

00:33:19.639 --> 00:33:21.200
This is just
a closeup of this.

00:33:21.200 --> 00:33:26.940
Basically I'm doing the same thing I
did with the pictures of the nesting albatrosses

00:33:26.940 --> 00:33:27.940
in
Antarctica.

00:33:27.940 --> 00:33:31.470
I'm shooting wide and I'm shooting close,
and if I do this, I have enough pictures to

00:33:31.470 --> 00:33:34.549
illustrate
all these different composition techniques.

00:33:34.549 --> 00:33:36.720
And here's
one more.

00:33:36.720 --> 00:33:40.940
I'm photographing this glacier, this
beautiful glacier up in Alaska.

00:33:40.940 --> 00:33:43.629
Fish eye lens,
15-millimeter lens, one of the widest lens

00:33:43.629 --> 00:33:47.990
you could
buy, and then I'm using my 100 to 400 to capture

00:33:47.990 --> 00:33:50.779
this,
to tell the -- to show the details.

00:33:50.779 --> 00:33:52.610
Details help to
tell the story.

00:33:52.610 --> 00:33:54.149
We can tell the whole story -- not the
whole story.

00:33:54.149 --> 00:34:00.169
We could tell a broader story by using
this wide angle shot here and then a closer

00:34:00.169 --> 00:34:01.169
shot.

00:34:01.169 --> 00:34:02.890
And
speaking of details, here's a nice shot of

00:34:02.890 --> 00:34:03.890
an iceberg.

00:34:03.890 --> 00:34:06.249
Kind of boring, but look what happens when
we move in

00:34:06.249 --> 00:34:07.690
for a closeup.

00:34:07.690 --> 00:34:10.179
This is taken with a 100 to
400-millimeter lens.

00:34:10.179 --> 00:34:11.990
I'm looking for patterns.

00:34:11.990 --> 00:34:15.730
Patterns are yet another composition technique.

00:34:15.730 --> 00:34:18.680
This is
an HDR shot.

00:34:18.680 --> 00:34:20.280
You guys into HDR?

00:34:20.280 --> 00:34:23.380
Anyone here into HDR?

00:34:23.380 --> 00:34:24.380
Just one?

