00:38:25.140 --> 00:38:27.350
So on the
back of your camera, you have a histogram.

00:38:27.350 --> 00:38:30.550
What that
histogram is telling you, is it's telling

00:38:30.550 --> 00:38:33.600
you about the
bright areas and the dark areas.

00:38:33.600 --> 00:38:36.220
If you have a lot of
dark areas in your picture, you can look at

00:38:36.220 --> 00:38:38.870
each -- like
you mentioned the zone system.

00:38:38.870 --> 00:38:41.710
You can look at your
histogram like you have a pile of bricks over

00:38:41.710 --> 00:38:44.970
here, and
if you have a picture like this with some

00:38:44.970 --> 00:38:48.930
dark areas
going to have bricks piled up like this way

00:38:48.930 --> 00:38:52.280
on this side
of your histogram for the dark areas.

00:38:52.280 --> 00:38:54.810
For the
highlights over here, you're going to have

00:38:54.810 --> 00:38:56.970
bricks piled
up like this.

00:38:56.970 --> 00:39:02.280
If you have a picture just taken on an
overcast day without a lot of highlights or

00:39:02.280 --> 00:39:04.490
shadows,
you're just going to have what looks like

00:39:04.490 --> 00:39:06.840
an even
mountain range, like this.

00:39:06.840 --> 00:39:11.040
When I talk about light, I do talk
about what I said before, that we have to

00:39:11.040 --> 00:39:14.820
learn how to
see the light, the contrast range in the scene,

00:39:14.820 --> 00:39:16.610
the
direction of light, the color of light, the

00:39:16.610 --> 00:39:19.900
quality of
light, but the histogram is your light meter,

00:39:19.900 --> 00:39:22.560
so this is
actually a very, very important thing.

00:39:22.560 --> 00:39:23.910
I don't use a
light meter.

00:39:23.910 --> 00:39:28.270
A couple of my friends still use light
meters, but -- you don't use a light meter,

00:39:28.270 --> 00:39:29.270
right?

00:39:29.270 --> 00:39:30.270
You
use a histogram.

00:39:30.270 --> 00:39:31.270
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Or a spot meter.

00:39:31.270 --> 00:39:32.270
&gt;&gt; RICK: Or a spot meter in your camera.

00:39:32.270 --> 00:39:34.060
The
histogram what you want to do is when you're

00:39:34.060 --> 00:39:38.540
shooting,
you want to move your histogram over to the

00:39:38.540 --> 00:39:39.540
right.

00:39:39.540 --> 00:39:40.950
If
you do a search on this, move the histogram

00:39:40.950 --> 00:39:43.470
to the
right, let's see how many pages you get on

00:39:43.470 --> 00:39:46.770
that, this is
the key because in your -- if this is your

00:39:46.770 --> 00:39:50.170
histogram
here, most of the information -- more than

00:39:50.170 --> 00:39:53.750
half of your
information is captured over here.

00:39:53.750 --> 00:39:56.030
If you have a
histogram with nothing over here when you

00:39:56.030 --> 00:39:58.810
try to pull
stuff out of the shadows over here, it's going

00:39:58.810 --> 00:40:00.040
to be
very noisy.

00:40:00.040 --> 00:40:02.580
