00:46:00.880 --> 00:46:04.770
to this
education thing, during the Vietnam War when

00:46:04.770 --> 00:46:08.830
the pilots
would go up, you know, on their bombing raids

00:46:08.830 --> 00:46:11.880
and they
couldn't land with full fuel tanks, right?

00:46:11.880 --> 00:46:13.870
They had to
get rid of them otherwise their planes could

00:46:13.870 --> 00:46:16.340
explode if
they didn't land correctly.

00:46:16.340 --> 00:46:19.780
They just dropped these
tanks like over beautiful villages like you've

00:46:19.780 --> 00:46:21.350
just seen
before.

00:46:21.350 --> 00:46:22.470
So you learn this stuff.

00:46:22.470 --> 00:46:26.140
This is part of being
a travel photographer.

00:46:26.140 --> 00:46:28.500
Getting back to that shooting
horizontally and vertically.

00:46:28.500 --> 00:46:30.280
This is Angkor Wat in
Cambodia.

00:46:30.280 --> 00:46:34.830
Nice enough shot, right, shooting
horizontally, but here's a vertical shot,

00:46:34.830 --> 00:46:36.490
an HDR shot.

00:46:36.490 --> 00:46:38.660
We can see the white clouds aren't overexposed
and

00:46:38.660 --> 00:46:41.580
washed out, yet we can see into the shadows.

00:46:41.580 --> 00:46:47.870
Now, one
thing on HDR is this: We can open up all the

00:46:47.870 --> 00:46:48.980
shadows,
right?

00:46:48.980 --> 00:46:52.930
But when we open up all the shadows our pictures
look flat.

00:46:52.930 --> 00:46:55.160
I want you to remember this when it comes
to

00:46:55.160 --> 00:46:56.160
shadows.

00:46:56.160 --> 00:47:00.900
Shadows can be your friend; shadows add a
sense of depth and dimension to a picture;

00:47:00.900 --> 00:47:04.260
and my friend
Frank Doorhof has this expression, "Shadows

00:47:04.260 --> 00:47:06.040
are the soul
of the picture."

00:47:06.040 --> 00:47:10.680
So, you know, just because we can open
up the shadows, it doesn't mean that we have

00:47:10.680 --> 00:47:13.540
to open up
the shadows.

00:47:13.540 --> 00:47:17.480
Another thing we have to do is add a sense
of depth and dimension to our pictures.

00:47:17.480 --> 00:47:19.980
We see the
world in three dimensions: Height, width,

00:47:19.980 --> 00:47:22.680
and depth;
our cameras only see two.

00:47:22.680 --> 00:47:26.660
Here this is a side of one of
the temples in Angkor Wat Cambodia.

00:47:26.660 --> 00:47:28.220
Here's another side
of one of the temples.

00:47:28.220 --> 00:47:32.780
If you shoot at an angle, you
can shoot sense of depth.

00:47:32.780 --> 00:47:36.240
If I'm going to photograph
this room right now here at Google, it looks

00:47:36.240 --> 00:47:39.360
very flat
shooting straight on like that; if I go over

00:47:39.360 --> 00:47:43.090
here, it's
going to have a much greater sense of depth.

00:47:43.090 --> 00:47:47.390
So try to
create a sense of depth and dimension in our

00:47:47.390 --> 00:47:48.570
pictures.

