00:48:13.050 --> 00:48:15.000
So I teach a lot of workshops
around the world.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:18.710
This is a workshop in Botswana, one
of my favorite shots.

00:48:18.710 --> 00:48:22.520
This picture illustrates a lot of
points in photography.

00:48:22.520 --> 00:48:27.290
One, the name of the game is to
fill the frame; Number 2, light the eyes;

00:48:27.290 --> 00:48:31.860
Number 3, have a
plain background; Number 4, use a wide aperture

00:48:31.860 --> 00:48:34.960
to blur the
background if it's distracting; and getting

00:48:34.960 --> 00:48:37.381
back to my
friend's -- my new friend in the front's comment

00:48:37.381 --> 00:48:41.090
about
light, I'm looking to expose for the highlights,

00:48:41.090 --> 00:48:43.380
the
brightest part of the scene first, which is

00:48:43.380 --> 00:48:44.380
right here.

00:48:44.380 --> 00:48:46.480
I don't want that overexposed and washed out.

00:48:46.480 --> 00:48:48.510
So
this -- and you want a little bit of expression

00:48:48.510 --> 00:48:50.710
on the
animal's eyes; he's looking for something.

00:48:50.710 --> 00:48:53.400
So this
picture illustrates a lot of different -- a

00:48:53.400 --> 00:48:55.240
lot of
different techniques.

00:48:55.240 --> 00:48:58.710
Here we see -- excuse me -- what
simple cropping can do.

00:48:58.710 --> 00:49:02.260
I not only cropped this
picture; I increased the saturation.

00:49:02.260 --> 00:49:04.910
How many people
sharpen their pictures here?

00:49:04.910 --> 00:49:06.080
Okay.

00:49:06.080 --> 00:49:09.690
The key to
sharpening the picture is using selective

00:49:09.690 --> 00:49:10.690
sharpening.

00:49:10.690 --> 00:49:14.140
Rarely do you want to sharpen the entire picture.

00:49:14.140 --> 00:49:16.450
You
want to sharpen just the most important part

00:49:16.450 --> 00:49:17.450
of the
picture.

00:49:17.450 --> 00:49:19.790
So here I'm sharpening the animal's face.

00:49:19.790 --> 00:49:22.010
I'm
sharpening the body, but not as much as the

00:49:22.010 --> 00:49:23.010
face.

00:49:23.010 --> 00:49:26.380
There'd be no reason to sharpen around this
animal

00:49:26.380 --> 00:49:30.290
because I want the attention to go to the
animal, plus,

00:49:30.290 --> 00:49:32.660
if you sharpen the dark out-of-focus areas,
that

00:49:32.660 --> 00:49:34.660
increases the noise.

00:49:34.660 --> 00:49:37.610
Always sharpen selectively, unless
you're taking a picture of a rose, then you

00:49:37.610 --> 00:49:40.690
want the
whole thing very sharp.

00:49:40.690 --> 00:49:43.870
But also I use a technique like
Ansel Adams used.

00:49:43.870 --> 00:49:45.240
Ansel Adams had a great expression.

00:49:45.240 --> 00:49:47.630
He said, "A picture's not done until I darken
the

00:49:47.630 --> 00:49:48.630
edges."

00:49:48.630 --> 00:49:52.320
Renaissance painters did the same thing, they
darkened the edges.

00:49:52.320 --> 00:49:57.850
So I darken the edges to draw more
attention to the -- to the main subject.

00:49:57.850 --> 00:50:01.160
If you go on
safari, having a good guide is the key.

00:50:01.160 --> 00:50:04.810
We're driving
around in the jeep -- or the Land Rover, and

00:50:04.810 --> 00:50:06.700
the guide
says, "Man, look at that lion.

00:50:06.700 --> 00:50:09.600
I can't believe that,"
and he's pointing to the lion.

00:50:09.600 --> 00:50:10.810
Well, we can't see it.

00:50:10.810 --> 00:50:15.970
This is why you want to go on safari because
if you look closely, you'll see that -- with

00:50:15.970 --> 00:50:18.690
a good
guide, you'll see that there's a lion hiding

00:50:18.690 --> 00:50:21.120
in the
shadows right there.

00:50:21.120 --> 00:50:26.300
One thing, by the way, if you're
into photographing birds around here, or owls,

00:50:26.300 --> 00:50:29.380
or any
kind of wildlife around here, if you want

00:50:29.380 --> 00:50:32.690
a better
chance of finding the animals rather than

00:50:32.690 --> 00:50:37.430
looking left
to right, like most of us read, search the

00:50:37.430 --> 00:50:38.860
scene from
right to left.

00:50:38.860 --> 00:50:42.240
It slows you down and it's really a much
better way to find the animals.

00:50:42.240 --> 00:50:45.200
You'll see if you're
outside searching for a subject if you move

00:50:45.200 --> 00:50:47.340
like this,
you're going to go faster than going like

00:50:47.340 --> 00:50:50.240
that because
you're used to going like this when you are

00:50:50.240 --> 00:50:51.790
-- when you
are reading.

00:50:51.790 --> 00:50:52.790
Okay.

